&quot;What are you working on that brings you to my home&quot;.<br>
<br>
Max shifted in his seat,  the beutifull but deadly dark elf always put him on edge.  He normally would have sent a courier as she stated but he needed to inspect the goods personanly and make haste  to complete his spell.<br>
<br>
&quot;My dear Najena&quot; he began. &quot;You are ever the inquisitive one, but you must know that I am far to much a gentleman than to bore you with such trivial matters;  I have come this day to renew my ties, the couriers can be far to impersonal. Too often I have denied myself the pressence of your beauty&quot;.<br>
<br>
She grinned that perfectly wicked smile obvious to his ploys but playing the game.  She above all eles enjoyed the intriuge and the verbal sparring.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well then you must stay for evening feast,  ne're could I let a good customer leave without enjoying my hospitality&quot;.<br>
<br>
She had him caught in his own net.  He had deffered her from her line of questioning only to be trapped here longer than he wanted and most likely into a dinner conversation about his work again.<br>
<br>
&quot;Of course Milady, how could I refuse such grand entertainment&quot; he smiled back at her and sighed in his head.<br>
&quot;Jobartick, gather our things we should freshen up from the trip for dinner&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes master&quot; and he clicked off to the coach.<br>
<br>
<br>
