She scanned as much of the room as possible from this vantage and moved back to asses her assets.  Her packs were gone and her cloak but she was still dressed and hopefully not well searched.  She pulled a loose thread from her leggings and out dropped a small pack.  She opened the pack to find most of her picks bent or broken but it was a start.  Moving to the door and sliding the largest intact pick into the lock she worked the mechanism, sitting in the darkness her thoughts drifted back to her childhood growing up in Rivervale.  It was a game they played,  to see who could get into the bakers stores.  Nightime raids on his store were common normally ending in severe lectures from the deputies but there were those odd occasions when they were successful and all ate sweet cakes and honey tarts covered in royal jelly. Darkness was not an issue, a lock of this type was childs play, her other senses navigated the lock and soon there was a tell tale click.<br>
<br>
She cracked the door open just a few inches to get a better look at the room beyond.  A square room lined with doors much like her own and the one ogre sitting at his desk, cake.  Silently she slipped out into the room closing the door lightly as she went; moving into the hallway in the western wall she stopped dead coming face to face with Gahhl.<br>
His meaty hand shot out in startling speed and grabbed her about the face covering her mouth not giving her a moment to react.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shhhhh. don't fight me or we are both dead&quot; her eyes glared at him as she struggled against his iron grip.<br>
&quot;Listen to me now or I'll leave you here&quot; she calmed noticably.&quot; If I had not made you look like my prisoner the guard would have killed you right there, now my buisiness in Ogguk is done so if you would like to leave with me stop fighting me don't say a word and get in this sack&quot;.<br>
<br>
In his other hand was a softwicker sack large enought to hold her easily.  He released his grip allowing her to breath and unfurled the sack motioning her to get in.  She looked up at him one last time and jumped in the sack as the sound of booted feet grew louder.  She felt motion and soon settled into a rythem of Gahhl's great strides, but although moving she felt completly helpless and hoped the ogre knew what he was doing.<br>
<br>
